snippet.textDisplay: @J P that’s a ridiculous position. Our immune systems exist through having contact with this pathogens, indeed we are constantly in contact with and composed of bacteria. It’s only when this relationship becomes imbalanced that we get ill. If we cut out those pathogens nature would only hit back harder with something more deadly. It’s a relationship, and the best thing you can do for yourself, and governments can do for their people is to stay healthy and fit and to encourage things that facilitate this.

snippet.textDisplay:
@J P Let’s hear it for the economy and work rather than bearing the ailments we have borne for millennia. What a crass attitude to wish away common colds just to benefit careers and incomes. We have greater problems caused by economic inequality that are due to the conditions within work exacerbated by people with your focus. 

I guess you’d love the Brave New World of Aldus Huxley but it had a catch. No one became old and wrinkled because they all died young. That’s the compensating mechanism for lives without disease. And the pharmaceutical industry will need to engineer that outcome into their disease beating products. Long living healthy people don’t make good business. Cold and flu remedies are big sellers. By eliminating colds and flu you destroy economic growth.
